            <fr:title text="Forester 4.2 › New query language › Relational queries › Querying a coslice of the transclusion preorder"><fr:link href="/foreign/www.forester-notes.org/jms-00WW/" title="Forester 4.2 › New query language › Relational queries" uri="https://www.forester-notes.org/jms-00WW/" display-uri="https://www.forester-notes.org/jms-00WW/" type="local"><fr:link href="/foreign/www.forester-notes.org/jms-00WS/" title="Forester 4.2 › New query language" uri="https://www.forester-notes.org/jms-00WS/" display-uri="https://www.forester-notes.org/jms-00WS/" type="local"><fr:link href="/foreign/www.forester-notes.org/jms-00WK/" title="Forester 4.2" uri="https://www.forester-notes.org/jms-00WK/" display-uri="https://www.forester-notes.org/jms-00WK/" type="local">Forester 4.2</fr:link> › New query language</fr:link> › Relational queries</fr:link> › Querying a coslice of the transclusion preorder</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Example</fr:taxon>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p>We can also write a query to compute the set of trees <html:em>underneath</html:em> a given tree in the transclusion preorder (including the original tree) — in other words, the coslice.</html:p>
            <html:pre><![CDATA[\def\query/transclusion-coslice[x]{
 \open\query
 \rel{\paths}{\outgoing}{\rel/transclusion}{\x}
}]]></html:pre>
          </fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
      </fr:mainmatter>
